================================================================================
  2. SHARED STATE  (src/agent/orchestrator.py + src/core/state.py)
================================================================================

The supervisor agent maintains a plain dict (matching EmailState TypedDict)
that is updated in-place as each tool result comes back.

Field Group              Fields
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Gmail Identifiers        gmail_message_id, gmail_thread_id, history_id
Raw Input                raw_email (dict from Gmail API / simulate endpoint)
Parsed Email             sender, sender_domain, recipients, subject,
                         body_text, body_html, urls, attachments,
                         headers, metadata
Classification           category, category_reason
Summary                  short_summary, detailed_summary, action_items,
                         deadlines, meeting_requests, payment_requests,
                         important_dates
Security                 security_findings, risk_score (0–100),
                         severity (Low/Medium/High/Critical),
                         security_explanation
URL Analysis             url_analyses (list of URLAnalysis TypedDicts)
Attachment Analysis      attachment_analyses (list of AttachmentAnalysis)
Reputation               sender_reputation, domain_reputation,
                         web_search_summary
Reply                    reply_tone, suggested_reply
Decision                 recommendation, recommendation_reasoning
MCP Actions              mcp_actions_taken (list of MCPAction TypedDicts)
Internal                 error_messages

The session trace (src/agent/trace.py) is a separate, parallel structure:
  _traces[session_key]  — ordered list of every tool call + result this run
  _emails[session_key]  — cached parsed email data (read by analysis tools)
Both are keyed by message_id AND thread_id and are cleared after the run.

================================================================================
  3. COMPLETE FLOW — START TO END (EVERY STAGE)
================================================================================

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 0 — STARTUP
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

1. Developer runs: scripts\start.bat
   └── Opens two terminal windows:
       a. Terminal 1: python scripts\tunnel.py
          - Authenticates with ngrok using NGROCK_AUTH from .env
          - Opens a public HTTPS tunnel → port 8000
          - Writes the ngrok HTTPS URL to WEBHOOK_PUBLIC_URL in .env
          - Keeps running (heartbeat every 30s, auto-reconnects)

       b. Terminal 2: python -m src.server.webhook
          - Clears proxy env vars injected by ngrok (prevents SSL errors)
          - Resets the Gmail service cache
          - Pre-loads the Gmail MCP server in-process
          - Starts FastAPI + Uvicorn on API_HOST:API_PORT
          - Registers routes: /, /health, /status, /events,
            /webhook/gmail, /test/simulate

2. Developer runs (once, or after 7 days):
       python -m src.services.gmail.watcher
   - Authenticates with Gmail via OAuth2 (browser opens on first run)
   - Calls Gmail Watch API: registers inbox monitoring on PUBSUB_TOPIC
   - Google will now push a Pub/Sub notification for every new inbox email
   - Watch expires after 7 days — must be renewed

3. Developer opens browser: http://127.0.0.1:8000
   - Dashboard loads, JavaScript connects to GET /events (SSE)
   - Dashboard enters live-listening state

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 1 — EMAIL ARRIVAL TRIGGER
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

4. A new email arrives in the monitored Gmail inbox.

5. Gmail API detects the new message and publishes a Pub/Sub notification
   to the configured topic (PUBSUB_TOPIC).
   Notification payload (base64-encoded JSON):
     { "emailAddress": "user@gmail.com", "historyId": "15XXX" }

6. Google Cloud Pub/Sub delivers a POST request to:
     WEBHOOK_PUBLIC_URL/webhook/gmail
   (forwarded through the ngrok tunnel to localhost:8000)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 2 — WEBHOOK RECEPTION  (src/server/webhook.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

7. FastAPI receives POST /webhook/gmail
   - Reads raw body, parses JSON, decodes base64 Pub/Sub data field
   - Extracts historyId and emailAddress

8. Deduplication check (historyId level):
   - If historyId == _last_history_id → skip (duplicate Pub/Sub delivery)
   - Else → store as _last_history_id, proceed

9. Returns HTTP 200 immediately to Google (must respond within 10 seconds)
   - All processing is offloaded to a background daemon thread

10. Background thread starts → calls get_history(prev_history_id)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 3 — MESSAGE DISCOVERY  (src/services/gmail/watcher.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

11. Gmail History API called with startHistoryId = previous historyId
    - Returns list of messages added to INBOX since that point
    - If history returns 0 messages (stale historyId) → FALLBACK:
      list latest INBOX message directly and process it

12. Deduplication check (message_id level):
    - Each message_id checked against _processed_message_ids set
    - If already processed → skip
    - If new → add to set (capped at 200 entries)

13. SSE broadcast: "processing_started" → dashboard shows email as "Fetching"

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 4 — EMAIL FETCH  (src/services/gmail/fetcher.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

14. fetch_email(message_id) called
    - Clears proxy env vars (proxy safety guard)
    - Calls Gmail API: users.messages.get(format=full)
    - Walks the MIME payload tree recursively:
        text/plain  → body_text
        text/html   → body_html
        attachmentId present → attachment metadata (filename, mime, size)
    - Extracts headers: From, To, Cc, Subject
    - Extracts URLs from body_html using regex
    - Returns structured raw_email dict

15. SSE broadcast: "email_fetched" → dashboard shows subject + sender

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 5 — PARSER  (src/agent/parser.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

16. parse_email(state) called synchronously before the supervisor loop
    INPUT:  raw_email dict
    PROCESS:
    - Extracts sender, recipients, subject, body_text, body_html,
      attachments, headers, metadata
    - Deduplicates and merges URLs from: raw_email.urls +
      regex scan of body_text + href/src scan of body_html
    - Extracts sender_domain from the From address
    OUTPUT: Updates state dict with all parsed fields

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 6 — SESSION TRACE INIT  (src/agent/trace.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

17. init_session_trace(message_id, thread_id, email_data=state) called
    - Stores the parsed state dict in _emails keyed by message_id + thread_id
    - Creates an empty trace list in _traces keyed by both IDs
    - Analysis MCP tools will retrieve email data from here by message_id

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 7 — MCP REGISTRY INIT  (src/agent/mcp_registry.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

18. MCPRegistry().initialize() called
    - Opens an in-process FastMCP Client connection to gmail_mcp server
    - Lists all 7 Gmail action tools and registers their schemas
    - Opens an in-process FastMCP Client connection to analysis_mcp server
    - Lists all 7 analysis tools and registers their schemas
    - Total: 14 tools available to the supervisor LLM

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 8 — SUPERVISOR REACT LOOP  (src/agent/orchestrator.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

19. LLM (Groq/OpenAI/Anthropic/Ollama) is initialised and bound to all 14
    tool schemas via llm.bind_tools(registry.tools_schema).

20. Initial message list is built:
    - SystemMessage: SYSTEM_PROMPT with tool descriptions + routing rules
    - HumanMessage: email fields (sender, domain, subject, body preview,
      URLs, attachment filenames, headers, message_id, thread_id)

21. LOOP starts (max MAX_ITERATIONS=10 iterations):

    a. LLM is invoked with the current message list.

    b. If the response contains NO tool_calls:
       - Loop exits → agent is done selecting tools.

    c. If the response contains tool_calls:
       - For each tool call:
           i.  Tool name and args are extracted.
           ii. registry.execute_tool(name, args, session_key) is called.
               - Opens an in-process FastMCP Client to the correct server.
               - Calls the tool function.
               - Appends result to session trace.
           iii. State dict is updated from the tool result:
                  classify_email       → category, category_reason
                  summarize_email      → short_summary, detailed_summary,
                                         action_items, deadlines, …
                  analyze_security     → risk_score, severity,
                                         security_explanation, security_findings
                  analyze_urls         → url_analyses
                  analyze_attachments  → attachment_analyses
                  search_reputation    → sender_reputation, domain_reputation,
                                         web_search_summary
                  generate_reply       → suggested_reply, reply_tone
                  Gmail action tools   → appended to mcp_actions_taken
           iv.  ToolMessage with result is added to message list.

    d. Updated message list is fed back to the LLM (step a).

22. After the loop, the last AIMessage content is parsed for the final
    JSON recommendation block:
    {
      "recommendation": "...",
      "reasoning": "..."
    }
    If no valid JSON block is found, a regex fallback is tried.
    If that also fails, the recommendation is inferred from which
    Gmail action tools were actually executed successfully.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 9 — TOOL-LEVEL GUARDRAILS  (enforced inside MCP tool functions)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

23. Gmail action tools enforce safety rules independently of the LLM:

    move_to_trash:
    - Checks session trace for a prior analyze_security call.
    - Refuses if no security check was run.
    - Refuses if risk_score < AUTO_DELETE_THRESHOLD (default 90).
    - Returns { "status": "refused", "reason": "..." } on refusal.

    label_as_spam:
    - Checks session trace for a prior analyze_security call.
    - Refuses if no security check was run.
    - Refuses if risk_score < AUTO_SPAM_THRESHOLD (default 75).

    send_reply:
    - Checks session trace for a prior analyze_security call.
    - Refuses if risk_score >= REPLY_RISK_THRESHOLD (default 40).
    - Checks classify_email result; refuses for Spam/Newsletter/
      Promotion/Shopping categories.
    - Retrieves sender + subject from trace email cache.
    - Skips if the thread has already been replied to (_replied_threads set).
    - Raises ValueError if body contains placeholder text like [your name].

    Simulation bypass:
    - If message_id or thread_id starts with "sim-" or "test-", all Gmail
      tools return mock success responses without calling any Gmail API.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 10 — FINAL REPORT ASSEMBLY  (src/agent/orchestrator.py)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

24. After the loop, the state dict is assembled into the final report:
    {
      gmail            → message_id, thread_id
      email_metadata   → sender, sender_domain, recipients, subject
      classification   → category, reason
      summary          → short, detailed, action_items, deadlines, …
      security         → risk_score, severity, explanation, findings
      url_analysis     → list of URLAnalysis results
      attachment_analysis → list of AttachmentAnalysis results
      reputation       → sender_reputation, domain_reputation,
                         web_search_summary
      suggested_reply  → tone, draft
      decision         → recommendation, reasoning
      mcp_actions      → list of MCPAction results
      errors           → error_messages from any failed tool calls
    }

25. clear_session_trace(message_id, thread_id) called
    - Removes trace and email data from memory.

26. final_report dict is returned from run_email_agent().

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 11 — SSE BROADCAST & DASHBOARD UPDATE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

27. _broadcast("analysis_complete", report) called from webhook.py
    - Serialises final_report to JSON
    - Pushes to every connected SSE client queue
    - Dead/full client queues are pruned automatically

28. Browser receives SSE event "analysis_complete"
    - Updates the feed item: severity badge, recommendation, risk score
    - If user clicks the feed item → renders full report cards:
        Decision banner (recommendation + reasoning)
        Risk score bar (colour-coded green → red)
        Security findings list (threat type, confidence, description)
        Classification + summary card
        URL analysis cards (per URL: suspicious/clean, reasons)
        Attachment cards (per file: flag, reasons)
        Sender reputation (web search results)
        MCP actions taken (status of each Gmail action)
        Suggested reply draft (with copy button, if generated)
        Pipeline errors (if any tool call failed)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
STAGE 12 — CYCLE COMPLETE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

29. run_email_agent() returns final_report.
    Background thread exits cleanly.

30. Server remains running, waiting for the next Pub/Sub notification.
    The cycle repeats from Stage 1 for every new email.

